{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16393"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16393"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.07,0.03,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9084"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman is reviewed on the medical ward for worsening confusion over the past 24 hours. She was admitted three days ago with weight loss and fatigue. She has no significant medical history, takes no regular medications and was previously independent and well at home. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She is clinically dehydrated with dry mucous membranes. Blood results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 98 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 180 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum calcium 3.8 mmol/L (2.2-2.6).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous normal saline","Intravenous zoledronic acid","Subcutaneous calcitonin","Urgent haemodialysis","Oral calcium-binding agents"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe hypercalcaemia (calcium \u0026gt;3.5 mmol/L) causing confusion, drowsiness, and dehydration. The combination of symptoms, anaemia, and renal impairment raises suspicion for underlying malignancy, particularly multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. Aggressive fluid resuscitation enhances renal calcium excretion and corrects the volume depletion that typically accompanies hypercalcaemia. Initial rates of 1000-2000 mL over the first 2-4 hours are often required, followed by maintenance fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous zoledronic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is an important component of hypercalcaemia management, but should only be administered after adequate fluid resuscitation and volume status correction. Bisphosphonates take 48-72 hours to achieve their maximum effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous calcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E can rapidly lower calcium levels within 4-6 hours but has a short duration of action and is rarely used as monotherapy. It may be considered as bridging therapy while awaiting the effects of bisphosphonates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral calcium-binding agents\u003C/strong\u003E like sodium polystyrene sulfonate are not indicated in the acute management of severe hypercalcaemia. They are more commonly used in chronic hypercalcaemia management due to their delayed onset of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E may be required in severe cases that are refractory to conventional therapy or in patients with severe renal failure, but it is not the first-line treatment. The initial approach should focus on fluid resuscitation and medical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe hypercalcaemia (\u003E3.5 mmol/L) is a medical emergency requiring urgent treatment.","Initial management of severe hypercalcaemia involves aggressive intravenous fluid resuscitation with normal saline.","Bisphosphonates are indicated in severe hypercalcaemia to reduce bone resorption and lower serum calcium."],"references":["Goltzman D. Approach to Hypercalcemia. [Updated 2023 Apr 17]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279129/","Walsh J, Gittoes N, Selby P, et al. Society for Endocrinology endocrine emergency guidance: emergency management of acute hypercalcaemia in adult patients. Endocr Connect. 2016;5(5):G9\u2013G11. doi: 10.1530/EC-16-0055. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1530/EC-16-0055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87208","links":{"self":"https://ap